Color alternates between greenish gray (GLEY 1 4/5G) and light greenish gray (GLEY 17/5GY) every 15-20 cm. There are planolites, chondrites, zoophycos and possible thalassinoides burrows through the interval.

Color shifts gradually to greenish gray (GLEY 1 6/5GY) towards the bottom of the section. Well-preserved zoophycos burrows are common between 54-94 cm.

Greenish gray (GLEY 1 5/5GY) intervals occur between 31-38 cm and 64-70 cm. Horizontal burrows are present at 4-6 cm. Vertical burrows are present between 71-78 cm.

Greenish gray (GLEY 1 5/10GY) intervals occur between 12-30 cm. The onset of this interval is gradational. Vertical burrows are present between 87-95 cm. Between 31-51 cm, there are sub-horizontal burrows with a dark greenish clay infill.

Some laminations pinch together and some between 77-79 cm are wavy. Some white intervals at 54-58 cm (contains some foraminifera) then 61-62 cm.
Color changes from lighter orange to a slightly darker brownish orange within this interval.
Pillow structure is present at 113-115 cm. A folded burrow(?) is present at 125-127 cm.

Sediments reworked is observed. There are several faint color contacts within this section but packages are not very distinct from one another. There are some parallel laminations at the top of the section (0-7 cm) that transition into a more bioturbated interval below.
A whitish layer is present at the bottom of the bioturbated interval at 28-29 cm.

Several thinly laminated intervals between 29-127 cm appear to be folded. Fold hinges are present at 48-51 cm, 89-90 cm and 94-103 cm. There are several ball-and-pillow structures at 38-41 cm, 79-80 cm, and 80-83 cm.

Thin laminations occur throughout the section and are bioturbated and wavy between 13-18 cm. There are several places where the laminations pinch out. From 34-52 cm there are no observable laminations, sediment was either entirely homogenized or was deposited as one layer.
Small light gray chondrites burrows are present throughout this section.
Color alternates every 10-50 cm from light yellowish brown (10YR 6/4) to light greenish gray (GLEY 1 7/10GY) then becomes a yellowish brown (10YR 5/4) below 102 cm.
Within the grayish brown interval (10YR 5/2) at 0-70 cm, there are pale green (GLEY 1 7/5G) patches.
Small white foraminifera patches are present; however, there was only trace amounts of foraminifera observed in smear slides.
Two grayish green (GLEY 1 5/5G) circular patches are present at 42-45 cm and 57-58 cm.
A grayish green (GLEY 1 5/4) circular patch is present at 5-6 cm.
folded/convoluted interval
White and black clasts are present throughout the section, pillow structures are observed at 26-31 cm.
Some folded laminations have black grains within it. In hand lens they look like chert(?).There is a chert nodule from 77-78 cm.
An orange chert layer is present at 148-150 cm. Some laminations are slightly wavy.

Laminations seem to be disturbed by low levels of bioturbation and some are wavy with soft sediment deformation. There is also color alternation between pink (5YR 7/4) and light greenish gray (GLEY 1 8/0Y).

A soft sediment deformation is present at 22-23 cm and some convolutes laminations are present at 23-24 cm. Three massive thin beds with flame structures at their base are present at 49 cm, 54 cm and 60 cm. Three thin laminations occur between 46 cm and 64 cm.
There is a siderite nodule and convolute laminations at the top of this interval.

Progressive color change from very pale brown (10YR 8/2) to light greenish gray (GLEY 1 8/10Y) at 63-82cm. There is an irregular clast light greenish gray at 78-79 cm. The base of this interval is marked by an erosive bottom contact.

There is a color change from white to light greenish gray to pink between 98-141 cm. There are 3 beds with laminations at 110 cm ,114-117 cm, and 132 cm, with erosive base and very thin sandy laminations at the top of these beds.
There are sharp boundaries at 2 cm, 8 cm, at 14 cm and at 43 cm, which separate laminate and massive intervals. There are some convolute laminations and bedding at 28-30 cm and 38-39 cm.
There is convolute bedding at 11-13 cm
There is an erosive contact at 62 cm and at 71 cm. There is color change along the section from light brown (7.5R 6/4) to light greenish gray (GLEY 8/5GY).
A convolute bedding is present at 79-81 cm with a small fault inside.
There is a color change along this section, from light brown to light gray (2.5Y 7/2). A greenish gray (GLEY1 6/10GY) silicified nodule is present at the bottom of this section
There is gradual color change along this section, from white to reddish yellow (5YR 6/6)
Strata is inclined 40 degrees. Slickenslides are present at 23-24 cm.
Slickenslide are present at 38-39 cm.
Very fine sand to clay, normal grading beds with erosive basal contacts are present at 77 cm, 89 cm, 92 cm, 94 cm, and at 100 cm.
Beds are more chaotic, with thin discontinuous green intervals at 29-62 cm.
The chert layer is very oxidized, yellowish-brown (10YR 5/8) in the base.
Beds are more chaotic, with thin discontinuous green intervals at 93-143 cm. There are also injections of soft sediment and a 1 cm dark green claystone at the bottom of the section.
A chaotic bed is present at 0-44 cm.
Bottom contact or boundary type: undulating or wavy boundary or contact [BJ80]

General interval comment: Recumbent folds at 58-127 cm and black layers at 57-65 cm, 73-77 cm, 81-83 cm, 92 cm, and 120 cm.

Recumbent folds along the section. A large black clast is present at 23-38 cm and smaller black patches are present at 3 cm, 6 cm, 7 cm, and 9 cm. There are greenish gray (GLEY 15/5G) layers at 19-20 cm and 40-43 cm. From 57 to the bottom the fabric becomes for mottled and massive and is a light greenish gray.

Convoluted beds range from having a smooth texture to looking jagged as a result of microfaulting probably from fluid escape. Large black clasts at 38-42 cm and 104-110 cm, and dark green clasts at 47-50 cm, 118-122 cm and 136-138 cm.

Bottom contact or boundary type: undulating or wavy boundary or contact [BJ80]

General interval comment: Bioturbation is generally low but is moderate at 84-91 cm. Throughout this interval there is soft sediment deformation (convolute bedding, some micro-faulting, and liquid injection). There were probably some parallel laminations within this interval but they have all been distorted. There are discolorations, to brown and peach/light orange, at 57-60 cm, 84-91 cm, 99-103 cm, and 113-120 cm.

The chaotic intervals contain some evidence of fluid injection, silt, and occasional micro faulting with some slickenslides. The color alternates between a light graying green (GLEY 1 7/10GY) and pinkish gray (7.5YR 7/2).

Color varies from pink (7.5YR 7/3), to pale brown (10YR 6/3), to light greenish gray (GLEY 1 7/10GY). There are a number of fining up sequences from fine sand to clay between 36-35 cm, 124-122 cm, 134-132 cm, 136-134 cm, 139-137 cm and 142-140 cm. Flame structures and microfaulting are present 53-55 cm, 73 cm and 116 cm. A greenish gray (GLEY 1 6/10GY) chert nodule is presnt between 36-35 cm.

A finely laminated interval occurs between 70-94 cm. The rest of the section is slightly laminated but this has been overprinted by bioturbation. There is a massive silt bed at 38-43 cm and a fine sand bed at 60-63 cm. There are a number of fining up sequences of which several have been overprinted by microfauting. There is also a chert nodule at 94-101 cm. Towards the base of the section, between 117 to 140 cm, there is a change in color to a reddish yellow (5YR 6/6).

Color varies from a white/white greenish gray to a red (2.5YR 5/6). There are fine grained sand stringer throughout the core. Several intervals are affected by microfaulting. Fine/wavy laminations are mostly concentrated in the lower portion of the core (102-126 cm). There is a fluid escape structure between 22-31 cm.
Color varies from a white/white greenish gray to a red (2.5YR 5/6). There are fine grained sand stringer throughout the core. Several intervals are affected by microfaulting.
Slightly lighter to pale olive (5Y 6/2) towards the bottom, at 100-130 cm. Between 109-111 cm, a red (10R 5/4) interval with white clasts is present.
Interval destroyed, not described
Every 5-10 cm, there is a change in color from greenish gray to yellowish brown (10YR 5/4). Some burrows (Phycodes?) are present throughout the section.
At the top of this section, between 0-35 cm, there is a greenish gray (GLEY1 5/10Y).
